DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260423
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260424
LOCATION:IU Europe Gateway\, Gneisenaustraße 27\, 10961 Berlin
GEO:52.490958;13.395597
SUMMARY:Locality and Context: Examining the Role of Place in Understandin
 g Media Inequalities
DESCRIPTION:Organized by Dr. Jason Peifer (https://mediaschool.indiana.ed
 u/people/profile.html?p=jpeifer)\, Dr. Mike Gruszczynski (https://mediasc
 hool.indiana.edu/people/profile.html?p=mgruszc) and Dr. Radhika Parameswa
 ran (https://mediaschool.indiana.edu/people/profile.html?p=rparames)\, th
 is workshop will be used to develop collaborative research projects focus
 ed on media inequalities and "locality\," involving scholars from both th
 e U.S. and Germany. These research projects focus primarily on examinatio
 ns of media-related phenomena that vary as a function of differences in c
 ontext: including but not limited to East vs. West\, North vs. South\, lo
 cal vs. national\, and urban vs. rural contrasts.  This workshop follows 
 on the heels of an online symposium\, held in January 2024 and organized 
 collaboratively between The IU Media School\, Freie Universität Berlin\,
  and the IU Europe Gateway. A recent collaboration between interested sch
 olars (nearly 20 people in total) held in June 2025 at the Annual Meeting
  of the International Communication Association (ICA) further developed t
 he plans for the workshop in Berlin.Keynote: "Locality Constructed\, Cont
 ested\, and Lived: Rethinking Media Inequality in Post-Industrial Communi
 ties" - by Dr. habil. Anke Fiedler (https://ipk.uni-greifswald.de/en/depa
 rtment/fields-of-work/communication-studies/chair-of-communication-studie
 s-with-a-focus-on-communication-ethics/dr-anke-fiedler-de/) from Universi
 ty of Greifswald.  Most people have never been to the Lausitz. Few have s
 et foot in Rotherham or Middlesbrough. And yet\, many have strong opinion
 s about places like these – shaped almost entirely by media narratives 
 that brand them "crap towns"\, "dirtholes"\, and the like. This keynote a
 sks what happens when we take these representations of post-industrial co
 mmunities seriously\, and what we can learn by listening to the people wh
 o actually live there.  To join the keynote session online\, please regis
 ter here: https://iu.zoom.us/meeting/register/i6jkRgUsQHuVGCs1wPAabg (htt
 ps://iu.zoom.us/meeting/register/i6jkRgUsQHuVGCs1wPAabg)Biography Dr. hab
 il. Anke FiedlerDr. habil. Anke FiedlerDr. Anke Fiedler is a habilitated 
 scholar in communication studies whose research focuses on communication 
 history\, including (post-)socialist transformation and memory studies\, 
 as well as public sphere and media change\, with a further focus on inter
 national communication. She has conducted research on topics such as jour
 nalistic practices\, media use\, and digital literacy in Sub-Saharan Afri
 ca and the Middle East. Her work integrates qualitative and quantitative 
 methods within comparative research designs\, frequently carried out in t
 he context of European collaborative projects. Her current research exami
 nes the interplay between media and social inequality in post-industrial 
 contexts in Eastern Germany and Northern England.
X-ALT-DESC;FMTTYPE=text/html:<p>  Organized by <a href="https://mediascho
 ol.indiana.edu/people/profile.html?p=jpeifer">Dr. Jason Peifer</a>\, <a h
 ref="https://mediaschool.indiana.edu/people/profile.html?p=mgruszc">Dr. M
 ike Gruszczynski</a> and <a href="https://mediaschool.indiana.edu/people/
 profile.html?p=rparames">Dr. Radhika Parameswaran</a>\, this workshop wil
 l be used to develop collaborative research projects focused on media ine
 qualities and "locality\," involving scholars from both the U.S. and Germ
 any. These research projects focus primarily on examinations of media-rel
 ated phenomena that vary as a function of differences in context: includi
 ng but not limited to East vs. West\, North vs. South\, local vs. nationa
 l\, and urban vs. rural contrasts.</p><p>  This workshop follows on the h
 eels of an online symposium\, held in January 2024 and organized collabor
 atively between The IU Media School\, Freie Universität Berlin\, and the
  IU Europe Gateway. A recent collaboration between interested scholars (n
 early 20 people in total) held in June 2025 at the Annual Meeting of the 
 International Communication Association (ICA) further developed the plans
  for the workshop in Berlin.</p><h5><strong>Keynote: "Locality Constructe
 d\, Contested\, and Lived: Rethinking Media Inequality in Post-Industrial
  Communities" <span data-teams="true">-</span> by <a href="https://ipk.un
 i-greifswald.de/en/department/fields-of-work/communication-studies/chair-
 of-communication-studies-with-a-focus-on-communication-ethics/dr-anke-fie
 dler-de/">Dr. habil. Anke Fiedler</a> from University of Greifswald.</str
 ong></h5><p>  Most people have never been to the Lausitz. Few have set fo
 ot in Rotherham or Middlesbrough. And yet\, many have strong opinions abo
 ut places like these – shaped almost entirely by media narratives that 
 brand them "crap towns"\, "dirtholes"\, and the like. This keynote asks w
 hat happens when we take these representations of post-industrial communi
 ties seriously\, and what we can learn by listening to the people who act
 ually live there.</p><p>  To join the keynote session online\, please reg
 ister here: <a href="https://iu.zoom.us/meeting/register/i6jkRgUsQHuVGCs1
 wPAabg">https://iu.zoom.us/meeting/register/i6jkRgUsQHuVGCs1wPAabg</a></p
